<p id="Par32">Next, we develop a joint distribution for the absolute mean temperatures in each time period, which correspond to the SDP temperature states 
 <bold>S</bold>
 <sup>T</sup>. To do this, we assume 
 <italic>T</italic>
 <sub>0</sub> = 
 <italic>X</italic>
 <sup>∗</sup> + 
 <italic>μ</italic>
 <sub>0</sub>, where 
 <italic>X</italic>
 <sup>∗</sup> is a constant reflecting the historical observed temperature in time 
 <italic>t−</italic>1, and recognize that the absolute temperature in 
 <italic>t</italic> is the sum of all the relative changes between 0 and 
 <italic>t</italic> plus 
 <italic>T</italic>
 <sub>0</sub>. The joint density of the temperature states is therefore:
